1.4:
Mountains dissolve beneath his step;
valleys crack open like wax at the flame,
like water flung down a cliff face.

1.9:
The wound is past healing.
It has crossed the border into Judah;
it has knocked at the gate of my own city — Jerusalem itself.

1.16:
Shave your head — shave it bare — and weep for your beloved children.
Make your baldness as broad as the vulture's bald crown;
for they are taken from you, carried off into exile.

2.10:
Get up and go — this land will not be your resting place.
You have fouled it with corruption;
now it will destroy you: a ruin that cannot be escaped.

5.13:
Your stone idols — I will destroy them;
your sacred pillars — I will uproot them.
You will never again prostrate yourselves before your own handiwork.

6.2:
Mountains — listen to the LORD's lawsuit;
you bedrock foundations of the earth — hear it out.
Yahweh has a legal case against his people;
he is taking Israel to court.
[The rib genre: mountains and earth are ancient covenant witnesses, as in Deut 32:1.]

6.8:
The answer has already been given, O mortal:
you know what is good.
This is all the LORD asks of you:
do justice;
cherish covenant love;
walk humbly at your God's side.

6.12:
'Your rich men are saturated with violence;
your citizens deal in lies;
every word out of their mouths is a fraud.'

6.16:
'You are living by Omri's code;
you are doing exactly what Ahab's house did;
you follow their playbook to the letter.
So I will make you a wasteland;
your people will be a byword of horror.
You will carry the shame of my people on your backs.'
